6 (b) A defendant is considered to be indigent if he or she the
7 defendant is unable, without substantial financial hardship to
8 himself or herself the defendant's or to his or her the defendant's
9 dependents, to obtain competent, qualified legal representation on
10 his or her the defendant's own. Substantial financial hardship is
11 rebuttably presumed if the defendant receives personal public
12 assistance, including under the food assistance program, temporary
13 assistance for needy families, Medicaid, or disability insurance,
14 resides in public housing, or earns an income less than 140% 200%
15 of the federal poverty guideline. A defendant is also rebuttably
