7 compliance plan a request that the MIDC serve as a clearinghouse
8 for experts and investigators. If an indigent criminal defense
9 system makes a request under this subsection, the MIDC may develop
10 and operate a system for determining the need and availability for
11 an expert or investigator in individual cases.
12 Sec. 13. (1) All indigent criminal defense systems and, at the
13 direction of the supreme court, attorneys engaged in providing
14 indigent criminal defense services shall cooperate and participate
15 with the MIDC in the investigation, audit, and review of their
16 indigent criminal defense services.
17 (2) An indigent criminal defense system may submit to the MIDC
18 an estimate of the cost of developing the plan and cost analysis
19 for implementing the plan under subsection (3) to the MIDC for
20 approval. If approved, the MIDC shall award the indigent criminal
21 defense system a grant to pay the approved costs for developing the
22 plan and cost analysis under subsection (3).
23 (3) No later than 180 days after a standard is approved by the
24 department, each indigent criminal defense system shall submit a
25 plan to the MIDC for the provision of indigent criminal defense
26 services in a manner as determined by the MIDC and shall submit an
27 annual plan for the following state fiscal year on or before
28 October 1 of each year. A plan submitted under this subsection must
29 specifically address how the minimum standards established by the
SCS H00942'25 (H-2) xq43rj

21
1 MIDC under this act will be met and must include a cost analysis
2 for meeting those minimum standards. The standards to be addressed
3 in the annual plan are those approved not less than 180 days before
4 the annual plan submission date. The cost analysis must include a
5 statement of the funds in excess of the local share, if any,
6 necessary to allow its system to comply with the MIDC's minimum
7 standards.
8 (4) The MIDC shall approve or disapprove all or any portion of
9 a plan or cost analysis, or both a plan and cost analysis,
10 submitted under subsection (3), and shall do so within not later
11 than 90 calendar days of after the submission of the plan and cost
12 analysis. If the MIDC disapproves any part of the plan, the cost
13 analysis, or both the plan and the cost analysis, the indigent
14 criminal defense system shall consult with the MIDC and, for any
15 disapproved portion, submit a new plan, a new cost analysis, or
16 both within not later than 60 calendar days of after the mailing or
17 emailing date of the official notification of the MIDC's
18 disapproval. If, after 3 submissions, a compromise is not reached,
19 the MIDC still disapproves of any portion of the plan or cost
20 analysis, the dispute disputed portion must be resolved as provided
21 in section 15. All approved provisions of an indigent criminal
22 defense system's plan and cost analysis must not be delayed by any
23 disapproved portion and must proceed as provided in this act. The
24 MIDC shall not approve a cost analysis or portion of a cost
25 analysis unless it is reasonably and directly related to an
26 indigent defense function.
27 (5) The MIDC shall submit a report to the governor, the senate
28 majority leader, the speaker of the house of representatives, and
29 the appropriations committees of the senate and house of
